## {{ rule.title }}

The [Form 1116](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1116) instructions say that, in general, foreign-source qualified dividends and capital gain distributions need a rate-differential adjustment on [Form 1116](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1116) line 18 (the foreign-source preferential income is scaled to reflect that those amounts are taxed at preferential rates rather than ordinary rates). The instructions also waive that adjustment when foreign-source preferential income is below the de-minimis amount (currently `$20,000`). [26 U.S.C. § 904](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section904&num=0&edition=prelim) is the underlying limitation statute.

This stage is a **gate**, not a calculation: it checks whether your foreign preferential income falls inside the supported zone (de-minimis or zero). If it doesn't, the engine fails closed rather than silently using the wrong limit.

For 2025, the gate result is **{{ rule.outputs[0].value }}**. With this status the FTC limitation calculation (US25-12) proceeds on the standard [§ 904](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section904&num=0&edition=prelim) fraction without an unsupported preferential adjustment.

